<HEADLINE>
FT  21 SEP 93 / International Company News: Profit warning hits Nike shares
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANK MCGURTY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SHARES in Nike fell sharply yesterday after the US athletic shoe and apparel
manufacturer warned that earnings in the current fiscal year would fail to
match 1992-93 levels.
In response to the announcement, Wall Street marked down Nike's shares by
Dollars 2 to a 52-week low of Dollars 46 in heavy trading. The stock, which
was hit hard in June after the company scaled back its growth projections,
has lost nearly half its value since November.
At the company's annual meeting in Beaverton, Oregon, Mr Philip Knight,
chairman, also announced that Nike would cut its worldwide workforce by 3 to
4 per cent as part of an effort to reduce costs by Dollars 50m this year.
The company said it was basing its earnings projections on a downturn in
'futures' orders, placed by retail outlets six months ahead of delivery.
These were lagging, it said, because retailers remained cautious in the face
of continued economic sluggishness.
In the first quarter of the year ended August 31, net income was Dollars
114m, or Dollars 1.49 a share, down 7 per cent from the comparable period
last year, when Nike posted earnings of Dollars 122m, or Dollars 1.60.
Nike said unfavourable currency exchange rates and higher US taxation were
largely responsible for the decline. If these factors had remained at 1992
levels, earnings would have been Dollars 1.61 a share, about the level
analysts had anticipated. The setback came on a 1 per cent increase in
revenues, to Dollars 1.107bn, against Dollars 1.099bn in the first quarter
last time.
In the US, footwear and apparel sales out-paced last year's levels by 5 per
cent. Sales of basketball shoes, Nike's mainstay line, slid 16 per cent to
Dollars 159m.
</TEXT>
