<HEADLINE>
FT  21 SEP 93 / International Company News: Wang out of Chapter 11
protection
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WANG Laboratories, once a leading US maker of minicomputers and word
processors, emerged from Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection yesterday as a
slimmed-down supplier of software for office computer systems.
Wang's rehabilitation was completed after it received court approval for a
financial restructuring agreed with its creditors. Unsecured creditors owed
Dollars 450m have exchanged their claims for ownership of the company, with
the issuance of 30m new shares.
Holders of the company's ordinary B and C shares have been left with
warrants, exerciseable into 20 per cent of Wang's shares in seven years and
nine months. The company said these were 'not expected to be worth more than
a few cents'. Both the shares and warrants will be traded on Nasdaq.
Wang sought protection from its creditors under Chapter 11 of the US
bankruptcy code in August 1992, when it had debt of around Dollars 500m.
