<HEADLINE>
FT  21 SEP 93 / Morgan Crucible reassures as profits rise 5%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD GOURLAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MORGAN Crucible, the UK- based materials technology group, yesterday went
some way towards dispelling concerns about its balance sheet and
profitability by demonstrating strong cash generation and a larger than
expected profit increase.
Reporting a 5 per cent rise in interim pre-tax profits to Pounds 32.5m, Mr
Bruce Farmer, chief executive, said the group generated Pounds 5.3m of net
cash after maintaining capital expenditure, compared with a Pounds 26m
outflow in the same period last year.
Analysts were equally encouraged that Mr Farmer had reconfirmed a commitment
to resist the acquisition trail.
Six months ago investors were concerned about the group's high gearing, the
use of acquisition provisioning that appeared to bolster profits and the
volume of corporate deals. Mr Farmer would not comment on progress towards
selling the Holt Lloyd car care business, which is considered non-core and
depresses group operating margins. The subsidiary made a Pounds 3m
first-half operating profit in a 'sparkling performance' and was likely to
make Pounds 7m for the full year, he said.
The pre-tax profit increase was struck on sales up 19 per cent at Pounds
401.6m, or an increase of 6.4 per cent excluding the effect of currency
adjustments and acquisitions. Earnings per share rose 2 per cent to 9.6p and
the group is paying a maintained 5.75p interim dividend.
Morgan Crucible squeezed Pounds 23.7m cash out of working capital - equally
from stock and debtors.
Net debt at the end of the period, however, remained less than Pounds 1m
lower than the year-end figure at Pounds 157.7m after adverse currency
movements. Gearing was almost unchanged at 66 per cent but the interest bill
was covered more than five times by operating profits.
Mr Farmer gave a bleak assessment of world markets. While group order intake
was up by at least 7 per cent, with Australasia, the UK and North America
showing gradual improvement, continental Europe and Japan were causing
concern. 'I do not think 1994 will be the take-off year,' Mr Farmer said.
At the operating level profits rose 16 per cent to Pounds 40.8m or 1 per
cent excluding the effects of currency and acquisitions.
The speciality materials, technical ceramics and thermal ceramics divisions
all advanced, while the carbon division was held back by the US.
Lex, Page 20
</TEXT>
