<HEADLINE>
FT  21 SEP 93 / Murray Johnstone agrees to US ownership for Pounds 49m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON, Scottish Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MURRAY Johnstone, Scotland's second largest independent fund manager, is
being sold for Pounds 49m to United Asset Management, a quoted US company
which owns 35 other fund managers.
Murray Johnstone, which manages funds totalling Pounds 4.3bn, will retain
its name and independence of operations, investment policies and personnel.
Four Murray Johnstone investment trusts - Murray International, Murray
Income, Murray Smaller Markets and Murray Ventures - own 75 per cent of
Murray Johnstone Holdings. They and the current and past employees, who own
18 per cent, have agreed to UAM's offer of new shares in the US company with
a cash alternative. The remaining 8 per cent is owned by Kemper Financial
Services of Chicago.
UAM is a holding company based in Boston which owns 35 fund management
companies managing a total of Dollars 86bn. It has a market capitalisation
of Dollars 1.1bn.
UAM does not manage securities itself and does not dictate investment
strategies to its subsidiaries, but it encourages them to compete against
each other. UAM will receive a percentage of Murray Johnstone's revenue.
Murray Johnstone said the deal would enable it to expand and to reward
staff. 'We're delighted to have found a solution which enables us to retain
our managerial independence and stay in Glasgow,' said Mr Giles Weaver,
managing director.
The Glasgow-based fund manager's expansion has been limited by its ownership
structure because the investment trusts did not want to increase their stake
in what is an unquoted company, already accounting on average for 4 per cent
of their portfolios.
A further complication is that The Cadbury committee on corporate governance
has expressed unease about Murray Johnstone's ownership structure, in which
Murray Johnstone manages the assets of its main shareholders, a structure
typical of a number of smaller fund managers.
In 1991 Murray Johnstone offered itself for sale to other fund managers in
the UK and Europe, but was unable to find a purchaser on acceptable terms.
The acquisition is UAM's biggest outside the US. It already owns Alpha
Global Fixed Income Managers and Ki Pacific Asset Management in London.
</TEXT>
