<HEADLINE>
FT  21 SEP 93 / Japanese discount rate cut to low of 1.75%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM DAWKINS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
JAPAN'S central bank cut its official discount rate early today by a
larger-than-expected 0.75 percentage points to a new low of 1.75 per cent in
an effort to stimulate the depressed economy.
Most analysts had expected the rate to be cut by 0.5 percentage points to 2
per cent.
The Tokyo stock market rallied after news of the rate cut, with the Nikkei
average climbing 250 points to 20,521 in early trading.
A central bank official said the cut 'should be appropriate to deal with the
current (depressed) state of the economy. It is a big cut, and we see this
as a decisive measure.'
Mr Hirohisa Fujii, the finance minister, said the cut would 'contribute
significantly to sustainable growth' in Japan in combination with other
government measures.
Domestic and international pressure for a cut in rates has been rising in
line with a stream of gloomy economic indicators.
Gross national product fell an annualised 2 per cent in the three months to
June and is probably still declining in the current quarter, putting Japan
into a 'double dip' recession.
The Bank of Japan last cut the discount rate - its key lending rate to
commercial banks - on February 4 from 3.25 per cent to 2.5 per cent.
The latest cut, the seventh since July 1991, should relieve much of the
disappointment that met a government pump-priming package of deregulation,
measures to pass on the benefits of the high yen to consumers and Y6,150bn
(Pounds 38bn) of public spending announced last week.
It included neither a rate cut nor reductions in income tax, as demanded by
Japanese industry. Possible tax cuts, a politically divisive issue, are
being studied by a government panel.
The latest cut will have a psychological impact and help restrain the yen's
rise, but seems unlikely to bring a marked cut in companies' borrowing
costs.
Some businessmen and politicians had urged the central bank to take bold
action and cut the rate by as much as one percentage point to help ensure a
recovery.
Commercial banks are expected to drop their prime rates on October 1, in
line with previous practice.
However, a decreasing number of banks maintain a tight link between prime
and actual lending rates because of the pressure on margins from the need
for heavy bad debt provisions.
Iron triangle softens image, Page 18
Leading contractor held in bribes probe, Page 4
</TEXT>
