<HEADLINE>
FT  21 SEP 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Tonight's funniest programme may well be Whicker's World (10.40 ITV).
Whicker is once again in South Africa, at a new 'pleasure park' called Lost
City which, we are told, cost Pounds 150m to create. Whicker's dry, stylised
and highly professional manner of reporting is very entertaining.
Vic Reeves and Bob Mortimer have taken their long stick and their big paper
bag and hopped across from Channel 4 to BBC2 where they begin The Smell Of
Reeves And Mortimer (9.00). The BBC describes their comedy as 'surreal', a
word which applies to Samuel Beckett and Spike Milligan but not quite
appropriately to Reeves. It would be pleasant to enthuse over Brighton
Belles, a British version of 'The Golden Girls', but as yet unlikely. The
series may still come right, but so far the funniest thing is the
desperation with which the producers are manipulating the volume slides for
the laughter track (8.30 ITV).
C4 shows the third and last of its documentaries about DW Griffith: Father
Of Film and tries to explain why the great pioneer worked so little for the
last 17 years of his life (9.00).
