<DOCNO>FT933-2095</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-DIUCIACKFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930921
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  21 SEP 93 / Liberal Democrats at Torquay: Leftward shift in strategy for
next election
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE shift to the left in Liberal Democrat policy-making was confirmed
yesterday as the conference endorsed a paper intended to set the framework
for the party's manifesto at the next election.
The clear rejection of laissez-faire economics and the emphasis on the need
for full employment were highlighted approvingly by representatives
yesterday in the debate on the paper, Facing up to the Future.
Even though the tone of the paper is already markedly more sceptical about
market mechanisms than its precursor, which provoked an angry debate at last
year's conference, some representatives who spoke yesterday expressed
concern that it was still too rightwing and expressed too much in terms of
conventional economics.
One speaker said the paper did not address the over-consumption of global
resources by the first world, while another demanded a commitment to reform
and regulation of City institutions. Yet another said that campaigning on
behalf of the lower-paid who were affected by the abolition of wages
councils was a vital element in ensuring that the Liberal Democrats did not
become 'yet another middle-class party out of touch with some of the real
issues'.
But the tone of the debate was overwhelmingly favourable towards the
document, which was praised for its statement of Liberal Democrats and its
analysis of the challenges facing the UK.
Some representatives, however, were unhappy that the conference committee
had refused to accept for discussion or vote any amendment to the motion
approving it.
Lord Holme, a leading figure in drawing up the document, said the paper
would help the party refute suggestions that it had no policies, and could
speedily form the basis of a manifesto if the parliament failed to run its
course.
The Conservatives yesterday stepped up their offensive against the Liberal
Democrats, who they believe pose the main threat to traditional Tory
strongholds in the south.
Mr William Waldegrave, the public services minister, said the party was
'notorious for chopping and changing their policies from one moment to the
next'.
Mr Gerry Malone, Conservative deputy chairman, joined in the attack, saying:
'Their strategy is shameless - to be all things to all men'.
</TEXT>
