<HEADLINE>
FT  21 SEP 93 / Liberal Democrats at Torquay: Party to temper its enthusiasm
for Europe
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LIBERAL DEMOCRATS are to tone down their fervent pro-Europeanism in an
attempt to maximise their party's appeal to disgruntled Conservatives in
next summer's elections for the European parliament.
Mr Paddy Ashdown hopes to treat the elections principally as a referendum on
Mr John Major's government, changing the focus from specifically European
policies.
In a calculated shift in the party's approach to Europe, its strategists
signalled yesterday that the Liberal Democrat manifesto would address the
concerns of an electorate which had become increasingly sceptical about
European integration.
Charging that the Conservatives were seeking to 'misrepresent' the party's
views, they said that the word 'federalist' would not appear in the final
manifesto.
Lord Holme of Cheltenham signalled the change of tone by stressing that the
party would not allow itself to be painted as an 'uncritical admirer of
everything that is done in Europe'. Lord Holme, a key figure on the Liberal
Democrats' policymaking group, was echoed by Mr Roger Liddle, the
co-ordinator for the European manifesto.
In an address to candidates for the Strasbourg parliament Mr Liddle said
that it was 'ludicrous' to suggest that the party favoured a 'United States
of Europe', warning that it needed to distance itself from 'grandiose
federalist rhetoric' which might lay candidates open to that charge.
Instead, the party needed to reflect the reality that Europe was in a phase
of consolidation. It should also avoid talk which implied that a 'single
currency is our only firm idea on economic policy'.
The injection of a Euro-sceptic tinge into the traditionally unalloyed
enthusiasm for Europe reflects the judgment that the party's best hopes of
success in the European elections is to defeat Tories in the south-west.
</TEXT>
