<HEADLINE>
FT  21 SEP 93 / Liberal Democrats at Torquay: 'Green' row looms over plan
for carbon tax
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PROTECTION for people who live in the country and would be hit particularly
hard by higher petrol and diesel prices through a carbon tax will be at the
forefront of today's debate about environmental taxation.
At a private meeting of Liberal Democrat MPs yesterday morning, Mr Malcolm
Bruce, the MP for Gordon, and Mr Alex Carlile, the MP for Montgomery, led
calls that the interests of rural constituencies should be stressed in the
debate in order to avoid a row over the impact of the policy on some of the
party's core support.
Support for a modified version of the European Community's proposal for a
carbon tax is among the most sensitive issues within the party. It carries
the risk of a conflict between the Liberal Democrats' commitment to 'green'
policies and the priority they attach to ensuring that people can still live
in the countryside. Most of the party's 22 seats are in predominantly rural
constituencies.
The paper that will be presented by Mr Simon Hughes, the party's environment
spokesman, suggests various ways of protecting rural people who need a car
from the impact of higher petrol prices, such as allowing them to pay lower
rates of local taxation, or enabling them to pay lower vehicle excise duty.
Given the party's campaign against the imposition of value added tax on
domestic fuel, he will also be anxious to stress a desire to compensate
pensioners for the increase in fuel bills. Investment in public transport
will also be highlighted.
</TEXT>
