<HEADLINE>
FT  21 SEP 93 / MPs dispute a Budget 'saving': Ivor Owen says financial
debate may be denied to backbenchers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE RIGHT of all backbench MPs to probe and challenge key tax proposals made
in the Budget will be removed if new procedures for streamlining debate on
the finance bill are adopted.
The Commons procedure committee has recommended that the entire committee
stage of the bill, when the provisions implementing the Budget proposals are
subjected to line-by-line scrutiny, should be handled by a standing
committee with a membership of about 50 MPs.
The two or three-day committee stage on the floor of the House, in which
every backbencher is able to vote if not speak in support of specific
amendments, would be abandoned.
Earlier this year some Tory backbenchers used this stage to join with
opposition MPs in condemning the extension of VAT to domestic fuel. They did
so in the knowledge that their protests would be widely reported on
television and radio as well as by the press. Such exposure is seldom
secured by speeches made in a standing committee.
Mr Nick Budgen, Conservative MP for Wolverhampton south west and an
outspoken critic of the policies which contributed to inflation reaching
10.9 per cent when Mrs Thatcher stepped down from the premiership, will
oppose the change.
Mr Budgen said: 'The whole process of the House of Commons being able to
protest at financial proposals will be weakened.'
Another critic is Mr John Townend, chairman of the Conservative backbench
finance committee, who believes that the change proposed for the committee
stage of the finance bill is a step too far.
He insists that 'really important tax issues should be discussed on the
floor of the House'.
Mr Denzil Davies, a treasury minister in the last Labour government, said
the finance bill was usually the most important measure in a parliamentary
session and if the procedure committee's proposal were to be adopted it
would be 'an extremely retrograde step'.
Until 1968 the entire committee stage was dealt with on the floor of the
House, with MPs frequently sitting late into the night poring over the
details of controversial tax proposals.
Critics said that the priority accorded to the committee stage of the bill
encouraged filibustering by opposition parties, with the result that complex
tax clauses were often dealt with by bleary-eyed MPs at two or three o'clock
in the morning.
This resulted in frequent complaints that such antics brought the House into
disrepute.
Splitting the committee stage so that all MPs retained the right to
participate in the examination of the most important aspects of the bill,
with the less controversial sections dealt with by the restricted numbers
serving on a standing committee, has proved a workable compromise.
In arguing the case for change the procedure committee claims that the
splitting device was no more than a sop to those who regarded the removal of
any part of the finance bill from the floor of the House as 'revolutionary'.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
