<HEADLINE>
FT  21 SEP 93 / GMTV aims for middle ground
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GOOD MORNING Television, the commercial television company, plans to
concentrate on 'the middle ground' in future and may drop cartoons on
weekdays in response to unexpectedly intense competition.
Mr Greg Dyke, chairman of GMTV and chief executive of London Weekend
Television, a GMTV shareholder, said: 'We've lost the kids.'
The children have left GMTV - which runs only a few minutes of cartoons
during the week - for Channel 4's Big Breakfast - except at weekends, when
GMTV runs more cartoons.
The Big Breakfast matched GMTV with peak quarter-hour audiences of 1.4m each
on weekdays, according to ratings published yesterday. BBC Breakfast News
had 1.1m viewers.
GMTV's reach - those who watch at some time during the programme from Monday
to Friday - at 11.6m outstrips The Big Breakfast, which has a reach of 8.3m.
GMTV lost Pounds 10m in its first six months on air although it is hoped
that cost-cutting measures will keep losses to between Pounds 2m and Pounds
3m in the second half. There are still hopes of reaching oper-ational profit
next year.
GMTV, which bid Pounds 34.6m for its franchise and also has to pay 15 per
cent of advertising revenue to the government, hoped to raise Pounds 80m in
advertising revenue this year. However, competition from The Big Breakfast
and the lingering effects of recession now make Pounds 60m the more likely
total, leaving it in deficit.
With Pounds 5m savings already made, the pressure on costs continues. For
example Central TV, which provides three news inserts for GMTV from its
separate areas, has now been asked to cut back to just one.
Mr Christopher Stoddart, GMTV managing director, said: 'We are fully sold
for the next three months but we could do with some more ratings points.'
He believes he has always been addressing the middle ground between The Big
Breakfast and Breakfast News. The challenge now was to improve quality, he
said.
</TEXT>
