<HEADLINE>
FT  21 SEP 93 / Executives feast on champagne and birdies
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM BURT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
OFFICIALS AT the Belfry golf course in Warwickshire were yesterday putting
the final touches to mobile offices and hospitality suites for the Ryder
Cup, which the organisers predict could attract more corporate attendance
than any other sporting event in Britain.
Companies such as IBM, IMI, Chase Manhattan Bank and the Royal Bank of
Scotland have taken hospitality suites for the European-US competition, each
costing Pounds 49,000 for six days.
The suites, known as 'platinum pavilions', have fax machines, mobile phones,
share information and dining facilities for up to 50 guests. Mr Richard
Brown, one of the corporate hospitality organisers, said: 'They can monitor
shares or drink champagne all day. It's up to them.'
All 38 platinum suites have been sold out, as have the less luxurious range
of pavilions, the gold, silver and bronze. Other executives are expected to
rough it in 250-seat restaurants which will cater for the 7,500 corporate
clients expected each day.
Organisers predict ticket receipts of more than Pounds 2m, which will offset
the cost of improving the course's greens and refurbishing the DeVere Hotel,
owned by Greenalls brewers.
The competition on the fairways is likely to be mirrored by the
transatlantic profile of the business guests, Mr Brown added. Executives
from British companies such as Bass will be able to rub shoulders with their
counterparts from Pepsi Cola over four-course lunches in the best suites.
The directors of Pepsi, however, will be arriving at the Belfry in grander
style than those from Bass, based in nearby Burton-on-Trent. Personnel from
the US company flew into Birmingham yesterday on a specially chartered
Concorde with executives from Time Warner, American Express and the US team.
</TEXT>
