<HEADLINE>
FT  21 SEP 93 / Housing bodies to fight fraud
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD DONKIN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE HOUSING Corporation, the regulatory body covering Britain's 2,200
housing associations, has urged its members to review their audit procedures
after a large-scale fraud at one of the biggest associations.
The fraud at Circle 33, estimated to have netted between Pounds 600,000 and
Pounds 1m, was discovered in its eastern area maintenance department.
Mr Grahame Coleman, in charge of contracts in the office, and Mr Graham
Dossell, a building contractor whose company carried out much of the work
under investigation, have been traced by detectives to Thailand after they
disappeared from their jobs earlier in the year.
Police, who want to question the men about the fraud, have sent a dossier to
the Crown Prosecution Service. They are hoping to apply for extradition of
the two men.
Circle 33 provides low-cost rented housing for more than 8,500 households,
mainly in London and the home counties. The association said yesterday that
it had centralised its maintenance contracting work and introduced new
controls.
The fraud, involving over-invoicing on contracts, led to the Housing
Corporation suspending Circle 33's 1993/94 programme of works worth Pounds
43m, including a Pounds 27m grant from the corporation. The programme was
reinstated in August after the association introduced new safeguards.
</TEXT>
