<HEADLINE>
FT  21 SEP 93 / TUC expects flexibility in public-sector pay policy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE TUC believes that the government's new public-sector pay policy based on
a cash-limits freeze for the next financial year may prove flexible enough
to defuse the danger of an co-ordinated showdown between the government and
public-sector unions.
Union leaders representing most of Britain's 5.5m public-sector workers are
due to meet at the TUC tomorrow to try to co-ordinate a response to the
policy, due to come into force in November. Statements by Mr Kenneth Clarke,
the chancellor, have suggested to the TUC that there may be enough ways
around it to prevent an over-rigid pay strategy.
The magnitude of future resistance to the government's public-sector pay
strategy may be evident later this week.
On Thursday Fire Brigades Union leaders are due to meet the local authority
employers in what they describe as a 'last chance' to secure a wage rise in
November based on the 15-year pay formula that links firefighters' pay to
the upper quartile of pre-tax male manual earnings.
If the local government employers continue to insist that they cannot
operate the pay formula this year and must act within the government's
current public-sector 1.5 per cent pay limit policy, delegates to the
union's planned recall conference are expected to vote for a strike ballot.
Contingency plans are in place to provide emergency firefighting services if
there is a strike, the Home Office said. It is understood that under certain
circumstances these could include deploying troops and Green Goddess fire
tenders.
Voting on strike action would start next Monday with the result due on
November 1. Possible disruption could start at fire stations on or after
November 8 but the employers believe the firefighters will not back the
union's strike call. They point out that the government's new pay policy
does not prevent a return to the firefighters' pay formula in the autumn of
1994.
The result of the strike ballot of 500,000 white-collar local government
staff belonging to Unison, the service union, is due on Friday. The members
have been asked to back six one-day strikes over six weeks.
</TEXT>
