<HEADLINE>
FT  21 SEP 93 / Police chiefs seek deal on Sheehy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE, Social Affairs Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CHIEF constables yesterday presented the government with compromise
proposals aimed at negotiating around some of the more contentious
recommendations of the Sheehy report.
The Association of Chief Police Officers said in its formal response to the
Sheehy inquiry into police roles and responsibilities that there were
'alternative solutions to the identified problems which are less complex,
less costly, and at least equally effective'.
Relations between Sir Patrick Sheehy, chairman of BAT Industries, and the
police service have soured since the report was published in June. Last week
Sir Patrick described police critics of his proposals as 'demagogues.'
The response seeks to cool the debate, expressing gratitude to the inquiry
for identifying areas of concern and saying many of the recommendations
offered 'substantial potential benefits'. But it remains critical of many of
the core recommendations.
It says that, while sympathetic to linking pay to appraisal, the Sheehy
recommendations for performance related pay are too complex, and the
recommendations for a lower starting rate would endanger recruitment and
retention of high-calibre officers. Proposals to abolish the ranks of chief
inspector, chief superintendent and deputy chief constable failed to
recognise operational requirements, while recommendations for fixed-term
appointments were out of all proportion to the problems of underperformance.
Moves already under way to introduce a flatter management structure have,
say the chief constables, led to the disappearance of 350 senior posts since
1990 - a figure that is likely to reach 1,000 in the next two or three
years.
The recommendations will face further criticism at the conference of the
Police Superintendents Association later this week. Mr Michael Howard, home
secretary, who is due address the conference on Wednesday, is consulting on
the proposals month.
</TEXT>
