<HEADLINE>
FT  21 SEP 93 / Labour to join attack on A-levels
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LABOUR IS expected to launch a debate today aimed at abolishing A-level
examinations and introducing some form of payment by graduates for
university education.
The announcement, as part of the launch of the third part of party's 'green
paper' on education policy, adds heat to the debate over university funding
two days before university vice-chancellors announce which extra source of
funds they favour. Last month vice-chancellors said they were considering
options including loans for tuition and an additional income tax for
graduates.
Labour's document is consultative, and so no definite plans will be
announced. Mrs Ann Taylor, the shadow education secretary, has strongly
signalled, however, that Labour should reject the present system of funding
where non-graduates in effect subsidise those who have had the benefit of a
university education.
Labour - like the university principals, who made it clear they welcomed the
party's change of direction - is considering either a system of loans which
would be repaid through the tax system, or a full graduate tax.
Mr John Patten, the education secretary, plans to announce his thinking on
funding in a speech to vice-chancellors at Leicester University tomorrow. He
is expected to offer further expansion in the sector if additional sources
of funding can be found.
Labour is expected to call for the abolition of A-levels, described last
week by Mrs Taylor as 'too restrictive and too narrow', in favour of a broad
restructuring of further education and the integration of more vocational
education.
In the last month A-levels have come under attack from employers and from Mr
Robin Wilson, chairman of the Headmasters' Conference, a group of
independent boys' schools.
</TEXT>
