was yesterday fined Pounds 22,500 and ordered to pay costs of Pounds 100,000
after admitting discharging dangerous chemicals into a main sewer near its
incineration plant at Pontypool, Gwent.
In the four-week trial at Newport Crown Court Rechem at first denied three
charges but then last Tuesday admitted them. It also admitted one charge of
breaching conditions of its licence to discharge into the sewer and was
formerly cleared of three similar charges.
Mr Ian Brown, for Rechem, said after the hearing that the company had only
admitted the charges because it wanted to appeal against the judge's
interpretations of the law.
</TEXT>
