<HEADLINE>
FT  20 SEP 93 / International Company News: Privatisation programme gets
under way in France
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN RIDDING and REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE French government's ambitious privatisation programme gets under way
today with the start of the pre-marketing process for Banque Nationale de
Paris.
The privatisation of BNP, the first of 21 state-controlled groups that the
government of prime minister Mr Edouard Balladur has targeted for sale, is
expected to raise between FFr25bn and FFr30bn (Dollars 4.5bn to Dollars
5.3bn).
Mr Edmond Alphandery, the economy minister, said the BNP privatisation would
be completed by December 20 at the latest, although most analysts believe
the timetable will be shorter.
The pre-marketing process, in which investors can make non-binding claims
for shares, will provide a measure of the demand for the issue. It will be
used to determine the price at which the shares will be sold.
According to the economy ministry, the government will offer about 40 per
cent of the share capital of BNP, or some 72m shares, for open sale. At
least half of this amount will be sold through a public offer in France.
About 12.5m shares will be sold to French institutions and some 23.5m shares
placed abroad, while about 8m shares will be offered on preferential terms
to BNP staff.
The government also confirmed that a core group of stable investors -
including Union des Assurances de Paris, the state-owned insurance group -
will hold about 30 per cent of BNP's shares after privatisation.
Individual French residents and citizens of the EC will have the right to at
least 40 shares in BNP. Investors who subscribed to the 'Balladur bond', a
government borrowing scheme, will have the right to a further 40 shares if
they convert some of their 6 per cent bonds into privatisation equity.
BNP chairman Mr Michel Pebereau yesterday repeated his forecast of a FFr1bn
net profit for full-year 1993, and said that the first half of next year
would be 'tricky', Reuter adds.
</TEXT>
