<HEADLINE>
FT  20 SEP 93 / UK Company News: Hozelock in Pounds 50m flotation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM BURT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HOZELOCK, the manufacturer of garden equipment, is to be floated on the
stock market in November at an estimated value of Pounds 50m.
The company, which is forecasting a 30 per cent increase in operating
profits from Pounds 3.8m in the 12 months to September 25 1992 to Pounds 5m
this year, hopes to raise up to Pounds 20m to fund expansion and reduce
gearing.
Mr David Codling, managing director, said the company needed to come to the
market to strengthen its balance sheet. The proceeds will repay bank loans
and redeem existing preference shares.
'Our aim is to raise enough capital to have very conservative gearing, so
that if an acquisition came along we wouldn't have to go back to the bank,'
Mr Codling said.
He expected many of Hozelock's customers in the UK, where the market in
garden products is estimated to be worth more than Pounds 1.5bn, to become
investors.
Sales to such customers have grown by more than 10 per cent a year since a
Pounds 24m management buy-out from Ropner in 1990. This year turnover is
expected to grow to Pounds 32m, against Pounds 27.3m last time.
Although the proportion of the share capital coming to the market has yet to
be finalised, the team of 20 executives who led the buy-out could see the
total value of their shareholdings increase to Pounds 8m if the market
capitalisation is set at Pounds 50m.
The company hopes a listing will help it expand operations overseas, where
sales this year are expected to exceed Pounds 8m.
Manufacturing of the group's 300 products is due to increase next year when
it moves its main plant from Aston, Birmingham, to a new Pounds 8.5m factory
on the other side of the city.
The flotation will be sponsored by Barclays de Zoete Wedd, and James Capel
will act as brokers.
</TEXT>
