<HEADLINE>
FT  20 SEP 93 / Treasury hires consultant to shake up top management
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH, Economics Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Treasury has brought in a management consultant usually paid about
Pounds 2,000 a day to change its organisational culture and increase the
effectiveness of its senior officials.
Ms Wendy Pritchard, who has helped push through change at big companies
including BP and Lloyds Bank is working with top Treasury officials under
Sir Terry Burns, the permanent secretary.
The radical move to bring in an outside consultant to shed light on the
Treasury's closed world is a sign of the pressure on the mandarins to
respond to sustained criticism that the department is out of touch and
inward looking.
Ms Pritchard, who runs her own London-based consultancy, has been hired to
work part-time. She is known in the consultancy world for working
intensively behind closed doors with senior managers to discuss how they
manage their workforce and relate to each other.
Ms Pritchard said: 'I find all this (publicity) slightly alarming as I
normally try to keep out of the newspapers.'
She is described as a 'an entrepreneur who acts as general practitioner to
top executives,' by Mr Richard Beckhard, a New York based consultant who has
collaborated with her.
Ms Pritchard is among a small number of people in management consultancy in
her field of 'change management'.
A close associate said she that would normally charge about Pounds 2,000 a
day. 'This kind of person does not come cheap,' he said.
Ms Pritchard did not comment on how much the Treasury was paying her. The
Treasury said it had nothing to say on an internal management exercise.
Ms Pritchard has previously been employed full time at Rank Xerox, and at
Shell International, where she worked for 15 years and was head of
organisational effectiveness. She set up her consultancy, Wendy Pritchard
Associates, about three years ago. Recently advised the Department of Health
on how to introduce change into the health service.
The consultant was introduced by Sir Terry to senior Treasury officials at
an unpublicised meeting in a Berkshire hotel in May. The gathering was
mainly for top 15 or so people who constitute the Treasury 'management
board' and who are in charge of the 1,500-strong organisation.
Mr Howard Davies, director general of the Confederation of British Industry
and a former McKinsey consultant, attended a dinner after the meeting to
review how the Treasury could change the way it managed decisions in its
field of economic policy and public spending.
</TEXT>
