<HEADLINE>
FT  20 SEP 93 / Observer: Top knob
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
With Peter Morgan, the fiery, Welsh-born director-general of the Institute
of Directors, stepping down from his Pounds 146,000-a-year post next year,
attention shifts to the question of his successor.
Amid some suggestions that Morgan would not have been entirely unhappy to
consider another term at the top, headhunters are seeking a man or woman
with 'vision, energy, drive and commitment' to occupy the spacious office
suite at the top of the IoD's gracious Pall Mall headquarters.
Morgan, who has managed to raise the profile of the IoD in his battles to
promote the forces of free enterprise, will be a hard act to follow. The
organisation, which is said to be engaged in a fairly heated debate over its
future strategic role, will certainly need someone else capable of making a
public impact like Howard Davies over at the CBI.
Word is that redundant politicians need not apply and that someone who has
already made a mark on industry would go down well. But if the IoD really
wants to break new ground and raise a few members' eyebrows it might
consider Mrs Ann Robinson, its own director of policy.
</TEXT>
