<HEADLINE>
FT  20 SEP 93 / The Liberal Democrats at Torquay: Ashdown says party 'near
breakthrough'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE LIBERAL Democrats were on the verge of breakthrough to the political big
time, Mr Paddy Ashdown, the party leader, said yesterday, as he underlined
the strength of the party's base in the country.
Speaking just ahead of the party's annual conference, Mr Ashdown highlighted
a survey, published yesterday, which showed that the Liberal Democrats had
established a decisive lead over the Conservatives in the south-west of
England and were making inroads into Tory support in the south-east.
The poll, by Mori for The Sunday Times, found that 46 per cent of those
questioned in the south-west supported the Liberal Democrats, with only 30
per cent supporting the Tories. This is almost a reversal of the parties'
positions at the general election.
Mr Ashdown said he hoped the conference would demonstrate the party's
maturity and ability to put across a clear message. He hoped its mood would
be 'serious, workmanlike and determined to ensure that the position we now
have, we hold'.
While emphasising that the party's base support in the country as a whole
was higher than it had ever been, he warned that Liberal Democrats still had
a long way to go and much work to do to build on the achievements so far.
His warnings against triumphalism were slightly undermined, however, by his
own refusal, in a weekend newspaper interview, to rule out the possibility
of his becoming prime minister. Yesterday he sought to play down the
significance of that, saying that every party leader wanted to be prime
minister.
This week's debates are seen by Liberal Democrat strategists as an important
opportunity for the party to communicate a distinctive political identity.
This is seen as crucial to its ability to turn the protest votes it has been
attracting into positive support.
The aim is to concentrate on policies in areas such as taxation and
employment, where the Liberal Democrats' ideas can be presented as more
radical than those put forward by either of the other parties.
Mr Ashdown said that 'opportunity' was at the heart of the party's message.
'The politics of the 1990s will be dominated by the party most able to offer
opportunity to every citizen in the land.'
He continued to resist suggestions that the Liberal Democrats were closer to
Labour than to the Tories, insisting that British politics was now
multi-dimensional. The party's co-operation with the government over the
Maastricht bill demolished, he said, the idea that the Liberal Democrats
were interested in creating a 'Lib-Lab' coalition.
Proposals for a greenfield development tax were approved by delegates at the
final conference of the English Liberal Democrats acting as a separate
entity. The tax is aimed at discouraging the building of out-of-town
hypermarkets and similar projects.
</TEXT>
