<HEADLINE>
FT  20 SEP 93 / The Liberal Democrats at Torquay: From Tokyo to Torquay -
Conference Notebook
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WE HAVE been here before. As the Liberal Democrats gathered in Torquay
yesterday for the start of the autumn conference season it was hard to
gainsay their claim that the third party is in better shape than at any time
since the heyday of the old Alliance in the early 1980s.
True, the row over the party's activities in Tower Hamlets soured the
atmosphere. Mr Paddy Ashdown's assertion that the national party had acted
swiftly to ensure errant activists were brought into line was less than
convincing. Senior party insiders admitted that the Tower Hamlets party had
been given a 'final warning' as long ago as 1990 to expunge any racist
undertones from its campaigning. Three years - and the election of a racist
British National party councillor - later Mr Ashdown's protestations of
ignorance offer a hollow defence.
But with Mr John Major's government engulfed by a semi-permanent state of
crisis and Mr John Smith's Labour party still fighting yesterday's battles,
the Liberal Democrats will not allow the issue to cloud their week. Mr Major
is unable even to spend a few days in Tokyo without being forced to call for
loyalty from his own backbenchers. So the mood in Torquay is understandably
buoyant.
Victories this year in Newbury and Christchurch and in the county council
elections have been followed by opinion poll ratings which more than once
have pushed the government into third place. The Conservatives' own analysis
suggests that a quarter of its remaining 32 seats in the European parliament
could be lost to the Liberal Democrats next June. Ironically, the mood of
anti-politics across the country which has restored the party's fortunes
holds out the prospect of turning the Liberal Democrats into the natural
party of government in the south west of England.
So Mr Ashdown's followers now see their real opportunity in the
self-destruction of the Conservative party. The talk of the 1980s - that
Labour could be driven back permanently into a few northern strongholds -
has been replaced by a sense that it is the Conservatives who are destined
for a long spell in the political wilderness. A glance at the continued
turmoil over Mr Major's leadership confirms that is no longer an incredible
claim.
The paucity of talent on the Conservative and Labour front benches has
obscured the obvious weakness of the Liberal Democrats at Westminster. No
more than a third of the party's 22 MPs could in other circumstances claim
real standing as national figures.
But by-election and council election successes won on the back of
disenchantment in the Tory heartlands are not enough - nor is the
unaccustomed and flattering interest now being shown by the media in the
Liberal Democrats' fortunes. Mr Ashdown, still prone to the hyperbole which
prompted him at the weekend to speculate on his own chances of reaching No
10 Downing Street, needs policies as well as popularity.
The party's latest policy document recognises the gap. The rather eclectic
faith in market mechanisms of previous statements has been replaced by a
more distinctive centre-left approach to macroeconomic policy. Full
employment - regarded for much of the 1980s as a goal only of socialist
ideologues - has returned to the stage as a legitimate objective of
government. The launch yesterday of a new policy-orientated journal by the
party's intelligensia - Shirley Williams among them - is intended to
reinforce the trend.
But some of Mr Ashdown's colleagues believe the leadership is still too
preoccupied with headline-grabbing gimmicks - the proposals for citizens'
referenda and co-opted members in the cabinet were the latest. Many of the
Liberal Democrats' instincts - devolution of political power, the
reassertion of the idea that individual opportunity and society can be
allies rather than enemies - strike a chord with a disenchanted electorate.
The mood of the country is not one susceptible to the 'government knows
best' attitude which sustained the Conservatives for much of the 1980s.
But as one senior Liberal Democrat said yesterday, a huge leap must be taken
before his party's status as a refuge for protest can be translated into
power. The bridge - a credible policy framework - has still to be built.
Then there is that other question: the Labour party. There has been
surprisingly little talk so far this week of that perennial third-party
issue - electoral pacts. Perhaps that is because no one now believes a deal
with Mr Smith is conceivable before the next general election. Many in Mr
Ashdown's party also are indifferent if not hostile to national rather than
local politicking.
But few doubt that the extent to which the Liberal Democrats are prepared to
acknowledge common ground with Labour will be crucial to their electoral
fortunes. The mould of British politics has been badly cracked. But it is
not yet broken.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P8651 Political Organizations.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>NEWS  General News.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
