<HEADLINE>
FT  20 SEP 93 / Resale of council homes 'blocked by loans policy'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM BURT, ROLAND ADBURGHAM and CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HOMEOWNERS WHO bought property from local authorities could be trapped in
houses they cannot sell, a study of building society lending policies says.
The study, conducted in the Midlands by a Birmingham City Council housing
official, suggests many owners will be unable to sell because of building
defects or the reluctance of lenders to offer mortgages in rundown areas.
The report concludes that a growing number of former council house tenants
who exercised the right to buy are finding that building societies have
become increasingly reluctant to offer mortgages on properties of
non-traditional construction - mainly houses with prefabricated reinforced
concrete or steel frames.
According to Mr Trevor Graham, the study's author, who questioned 15 lenders
during academic research on the subject, some societies will not offer loans
on such housing - favoured by councils because it was quick and cheap to
build - as it has a reputation for cracking and corrosion which makes it a
bad risk.
The problem has been raised in parliament, where the Commons environment
committee has demanded a government inquiry into the growing numbers of
'unsaleable right-to-buy properties'.
Mr Alex Smith, a Birmingham chartered surveyor, said: 'The societies have
made too many bad loans, so now they're much tougher. On every property they
ask, 'Has it got bricks in it?''
Leading building societies deny refusing to lend on properties of
non-traditional construction. Each case is treated individually, according
to societies such as Nationwide and Halifax, which add that their mortgage
managers have not been advised to steer clear of former council properties.
</TEXT>
