<HEADLINE>
FT  20 SEP 93 / Warning on dairy prices is attacked
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DEBORAH HARGREAVES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR ANDREW DARE, chief executive of the Milk Marketing Board, has attacked
claims by some of the UK's large dairy companies that consumer milk prices
will rise when the Pounds 3.3bn industry enters a free market next April.
Mr Dare said: 'There will certainly be some rises in price, but they should
be modest.' He believes consumer prices should not rise by more than 8 per
cent and will be kept down by intense competition among dairy companies.
The UK's dairy industry became embroiled in a row about pricing after Mr
Dare held out the prospect of higher prices to farmers for their supplies if
they joined Milk Marque, the successor to the Milk Marketing Board, which is
to be abolished.
Mr Dare believes that the removal of the current pricing system, which
charges dairy company customers different prices for milk depending on its
end-use, will see consumers paying higher prices for products such as butter
or cheese.
He said: 'But prices to UK farmers are not high by European standards. I
don't see why UK farmers shouldn't get higher prices while consumer price
rises are kept at a modest level.'
A report by Adas, the government's farm development service, says farmers
should be wary of counting on higher payments over the long term.
Mr John Sumner, head of dairy development at Adas, said: 'The milk price
could stay good for a couple of years as milk buyers bid for supplies, but
after that the effects of a Gatt settlement will bring pressure on prices.'
The Adas report, which is due to be released on Wednesday, urges the
industry to become more involved in higher-quality, added-value products
such as dairy desserts, fromage frais and soft cheeses as a way of competing
against imports.
The UK produces only 85 per cent of its own dairy needs, and is constrained
by European Community quotas from raising output. But countries such as The
Netherlands and Denmark produce two to three times their own consumption and
look to the UK as a lucrative export market. The UK's dairy trade deficit
was Pounds 609m last year.
The abolition of the Milk Marketing Board introduces competition into milk
buying for the first time since the 1930s, and many UK dairy companies are
looking to buy directly from farmers.
The forces of competition could accelerate the rationalisation of the dairy
industry, with many plants closing because of over-capacity. The size of
dairy farms is expected to increase as many smaller producers go out of
business.
Mr Sumner believes that a third of the UK's 29,000 dairy farmers will leave
the business by the year 2000, pushed by pressure on incomes and tempted by
high asset values - such as the price for selling EC quota.
</TEXT>
