<HEADLINE>
FT  20 SEP 93 / Birt hits out on BBC licence fee
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE BBC has gone on the offensive to try to defend the value of its licence
fee, which raises about Pounds 1.5bn a year.
Mr John Birt, the BBC director-general, speaking at the Cambridge Convention
of the Royal Television Society at the weekend, called on the government to
preserve the value of the licence fee and continue to link it with the
retail prices index.
The government is expected to decide in November on the level of the
licence, currently Pounds 83, for the last three years of the BBC's present
royal charter, which runs out at the end of 1996.
'I don't believe that the organisation can sensibly be pushed further,' said
Mr Birt, who earlier told the convention that in addition to Pounds 100m
savings this financial year, savings of Pounds 50m were planned for next
year and Pounds 25m the year after.
He added: 'The time will come - and it's not too far away - when major
efficiency savings on the BBC are no longer possible. At that point
preserving, let alone developing, our programme services will be at an end,
unless there is a real increase in the licence fee.'
Mr Michael Grade, chief executive of Channel 4, said the corporation faced a
poverty spiral, where the more they saved the more the government took from
it.
He said: 'As a citizen, and as a licence payer, and as a broadcaster I will
go to the barricade for the BBC licence fee.'
At the convention Mr Leslie Hill, chairman and chief executive of Central
Independent Television, re-opened the issue of changes in ownership in ITV -
a possibility being considered by the government.
He said that without relaxation of the rules that prevent any of the nine
largest ITV companies taking each other over, British commercial television
would be increasingly dominated by US, continental European and possibly
Japanese companies.
'If we can't grow we can't compete,' Mr Hill said.
</TEXT>
