<HEADLINE>
FT  20 SEP 93 / Recovery 'slowed by European recession'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRONWEN MADDOX
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE ECONOMIC recovery will be 'patchy and anaemic' because of recession in
continental Europe, says Oxford Economic Forecasting.
Weakness in the financial and construction sectors is also holding back
growth, the UK-based independent consultancy says in its latest review of
industrial prospects, published today.
Mr John Walker, the group's chief economist, said: 'The sectoral impact of
the recession has been unusual, to say the least.' The group says that the
construction sector, which normally leads recovery, is still suffering from
falling output 'mainly because of the excesses of the 1980s'.
In spite of those warnings, the report expects a 'sustained recovery' with
GDP growth of 1.9 per cent this year and 3.2 per cent next year, following
falls in the past two years.
In contrast to the forecasts of some other economists, the group predicts
that the government's proposal to impose value added tax on domestic fuel in
stages over the next three years will have a big effect on demand for fuel.
The output of the fuels and water sector will be nearly 2 per cent lower in
1996, it says.
The latest set of economic forecasts from Coopers &amp; Lybrand, the accountancy
and consultancy group, agrees that the recovery will be sluggish and patchy.
The report, which blames the weakness on high consumer debt among other
factors, expects slower growth than the Oxford forecasts - only 1.5 per cent
this year and 2 per cent next year.
Ms Rosemary Radcliffe, Coopers' head of economics, said that in the next 10
to 15 years even if Continental prospects improved, the emerging Asian
markets would be the key to high growth.
</TEXT>
