<HEADLINE>
FT  20 SEP 93 / Umpire refuses to play games: The race for the 2000 Olympic
Games will be decided on Thursday / A look at the prizes to be won
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DANIEL GREEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
'I HAD three letters from Chinese people this morning,' said Dame Mary Glen
Haig last week. 'But it doesn't make any difference who writes.'
After 11 years as one of the UK's two representatives to the International
Olympic Committee - the other is the Princess Royal - Dame Mary is used to
resisting the blandishments of Olympics-hungry cities such as Beijing.
'When Tokyo wanted the games I got postcards from Japanese schoolchildren,'
she said.
For Dame Mary, who fenced for Britain in four consecutive Olympics from
1948, the decision on venue is simple.
You consider the skills of the local organisers. You ensure they have the
required money and ability. 'Then you look at it from the athlete's point of
view,' she said. 'How far, for example, is the athletes' village from the
arena.'
To her, the process seems to be rather tedious. 'The thing that captures the
imagination,' she said, 'is working with the IOC medical commission, which
deals among other things with the misuse of drugs by athletes.'
Even this issue has been linked with the bids this year. Chinese women
athletes have broken world records by huge margins, triggering speculation
of help from drugs.
At 75, Dame Mary must retire from the IOC after this week's vote. Her
businesslike self-control only wavered when she talked of what the
atmosphere would be like when this year's voting was over. There would be an
end-of-term feeling, she said, 'and a party.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P794  Commercial Sports.
    P799  Miscellaneous Amusement, Recreation Services.
</IN>
<XX>
