<HEADLINE>
FT  20 SEP 93 / Key senator urges return of Nafta to White House
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NANCY DUNNE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
CHAIRMAN of the key Senate Finance Committee, Senator Daniel Patrick
Moynihan, yesterday said the North American Free Trade Agreement could be
returned by Congress to the White House for further negotiation, a move
which might effectively kill the pact.
'I am a free trader with free countries,' said Mr Moynihan, whose committee
has jurisdiction over all trade legislation. His reservations, expressed in
an interview on US television yesterday, indicate that the pact could be in
as much trouble in the Senate as in the House, where it is deeply unpopular.
Senator Moynihan is a long-time ally of the labour movement, which is
holding anti-Nafta rallies all over the country.
'The Mexican government is an authoritarian government,' he said. 'They
don't have an independent judiciary. They don't have free elections. They
have lots of laws which they enforce very selectively.'
This raised the question of how much the US should depend on Mexico's
institutions for enforcement of Nafta, he said.
In the hope of pacifying the labour movement, the Clinton administration
negotiated a side agreement to ensure enforcement of Mexico's progressive
labour laws. But the Mexican government refused to commit itself to easing
restrictions on labour unions.
American unions have made the defeat of Nafta their top priority. In the
current atmosphere of job insecurity the trade agreement threatens to become
as divisive an issue as any in recent memory.
Mr David Bergen, a senior presidential adviser, acknowledged Nafta would
lose if voted on today. But 'public opinion is very malleable,' he said.
</TEXT>
